{"title_page": "Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall", "text_new": "'''Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall''' (died 1606) was a Scottish landowner, soldier, and diplomat.\n\nAndrew Keith was a grandson of [[William Keith, 4th Earl Marischal]], a son of the [[Deer Abbey|Commendator of Deer]]. He spent his early career as a soldier in the service of Sweden, as a supporter and later an official of [[John III of Sweden]], and had been made Baron Forsholm.<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 17-18: Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 209.</ref>\n\n==Anna of Denmark==\nAndrew Keith was knighted and created [[Lord Dingwall]] before 1584 by [[James VI of Scotland]]. He went to Denmark to negotiate the king's marriage to [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>George Crawfurd, ''The peerage of Scotland : containing an historical and genealogical account of the nobility of that kingdom'' (Edinburgh, 1716), p. 92.</ref> In July 1589 Dingwall and his fellow ambassadors [[George Young (diplomat)|George Young]], and [[John Skene, Lord Curriehill|John Skene]] came to [[Boyne Castle]] to bring James VI news from Denmark of the progress of the marriage negotiations and preparations of ships, jewels, and a silver coach for Anne of Denmark. However, in Denmark the presence of Andrew Keith in the embassy, as a man in Swedish service, had caused offence.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 124: David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), p. 21.</ref> [[John Colville (c. 1540\u20131605)|John Colville]], who was at Aberdeen with the royal party, heard that the ambassadors had not seen Anne of Denmark in person. James VI decided to send Dingwall back to Denmark.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 123-30.</ref> [[Thomas Fowler (courtier)|Thomas Fowler]], also at Aberdeen, had heard a rumour that the embassy had caused some confusion in Denmark, the marriage being considered as settled, and costly preparations in hand, a circumstance that could bring disgrace to the lady and the Danish council \"in most parts of Europe\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 131-132.</ref>\n\nDingwall returned from Denmark on September 1589 and reported that he had seen Anna of Denmark and her fleet, commanded by the Danish admirals [[Peder Munk]] and Henrik Gyldenstierne, at the northern tip of Denmark, at [[Skagen]]. The English ambassador [[William Ashby (died 1593)|William Ashby]] heard that the queen would arrive in five days in the best of conditions, and the wind was favourable.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 155, 163-4.</ref> \n\nDingwall was picked to travel to Norway to fetch the queen, then included in the king's party in Norway and Denmark.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 170-1.</ref>  In January they travelled overland through a part of Sweden, Anne of Denmark and James VI in sledges sent by her mother [[Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]]. John III king of Sweden had sent special instructions that Andrew Keith and [[Axel Gyldenstierne]] should on no account be allowed in the fortress of [[\u00c4lvsborg fortress|\u00c4lvsborg]] at the mouth of the river [[G\u00f6ta \u00e4lv|G\u00f6ta]].<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 97-99.</ref>\n\n==Sweden again==\nAndrew Keith resigned his lands to Sir [[William Keith of Delny]] and returned to Sweden. He came to Scotland in January 1598 on a mission from the king of Poland, and James VI gave him a gold chain worth 300 crowns. He intended to recruit men for service in Sweden but according to [[Roger Aston]] he had no money to enlist them, and people were discouraged because earlier recruits had been \"cruelly slain.\"<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 155.</ref>\n\nHe was exiled from Sweden after the coup in 1598 and died in Paris in 1606.<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 17-18: Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 209.</ref>\n\nAndrew Keith married Elizabeth Grip in 1574. She wrote to the Earl Marischal in August 1584 thanking him for the help he had given them.<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 160.</ref> They had a house in Stockhom, and ran a network of intelligence agents in Sweden.<ref>[https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1534 'KEITH, ANDREW (SSNE 1534)', University of St Andrews, SSNE database].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1534 'KEITH, ANDREW (SSNE 1534)', University of St Andrews, Scotland, Scandinavia and Northern European Biographical Database].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keith, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1606 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall''' (died 1606) was a Scottish landowner, soldier, and diplomat.\n\nAndrew Keith was a grandson of [[William Keith, 4th Earl Marischal]], a son of the [[Deer Abbey|Commendator of Deer]]. He spent his early career as a soldier in the service of Sweden, as a supporter and later an official of [[John III of Sweden]], and had been made Baron Forsholm.<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 17-18: Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 209.</ref>\n\nAndrew Keith was knighted and created [[Lord Dingwall]] before 1584 by [[James VI of Scotland]]. He went to Denmark to negotiate the king's marriage to [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>George Crawfurd, ''The peerage of Scotland : containing an historical and genealogical account of the nobility of that kingdom'' (Edinburgh, 1716), p. 92.</ref> In July 1589 Dingwall and his fellow ambassadors [[George Young (diplomat)|George Young]], and [[John Skene, Lord Curriehill|John Skene]] came to [[Boyne Castle]] to bring James VI news from Denmark of the progress of the marriage negotiations and preparations of ships, jewels, and a silver coach for Anne of Denmark. However, in Denmark the presence of Andrew Keith in the embassy, as a man in Swedish service, had caused offence.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 124: David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), p. 21.</ref> [[John Colville (c. 1540\u20131605)|John Colville]], who was at Aberdeen with the royal party, heard that the ambassadors had not seen Anne of Denmark in person. James VI decided to send Dingwall back to Denmark.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 123-30.</ref> [[Thomas Fowler (courtier)|Thomas Fowler]], also at Aberdeen, had heard a rumour that the embassy had caused some confusion in Denmark, the marriage being considered as settled, and costly preparations in hand, a circumstance that could bring disgrace to the lady and the Danish council \"in most parts of Europe\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 131-132.</ref>\n\nDingwall returned from Denmark on September 1589 and reported that he had seen Anne of Denmark and her fleet, commanded by the Danish admirals [[Peder Munk]] and Henrik Gyldenstierne, at the northern tip of Denmark, at [[Skagen]]. The English ambassador [[William Ashby (died 1593)|William Ashby]] heard that the queen would arrive in five days in the best of conditions, and the wind was favourable.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 155, 163-4.</ref> \n\nDingwall was picked to travel to Norway to fetch the queen, then included in the king's party in Norway and Denmark.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 170-1.</ref>  In January they travelled overland through a part of Sweden, Anne of Denmark and James VI in sledges sent by her mother [[Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]]. John III king of Sweden had sent special instructions that Andrew Keith and [[Axel Gyldenstierne]] should on no account be allowed in the fortress of [[\u00c4lvsborg fortress|\u00c4lvsborg]] at the mouth of the river [[G\u00f6ta \u00e4lv|G\u00f6ta]].<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 97-99.</ref>\n\n==Sweden again==\nAndrew Keith resigned his lands to Sir [[William Keith of Delny]] and returned to Sweden. He came to Scotland in January 1598 on a mission from the king of Poland, and James VI gave him a gold chain worth 300 crowns. He intended to recruit men for service in Sweden but according to [[Roger Aston]] he had no money to enlist them, and people were discouraged because earlier recruits had been \"cruelly slain.\"<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 155.</ref>\n\nHe was exiled from Sweden after the coup in 1598 and died in Paris in 1606.<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 17-18: Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 209.</ref>\n\nAndrew Keith married Elizabeth Grip in 1574. She wrote to the Earl Marischal in August 1584 thanking him for the help he had given them.<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 160.</ref> They had a house in Stockhom, and ran a network of intelligence agents in Sweden.<ref>[https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1534 'KEITH, ANDREW (SSNE 1534)', University of St Andrews, SSNE database].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1534 'KEITH, ANDREW (SSNE 1534)', University of St Andrews, Scotland, Scandinavia and Northern European Biographical Database].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keith, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1606 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Keith,_Lord_Dingwall"}
{"title_page": "George Alston-Roberts-West", "text_new": "[[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-Colonel]] '''George Arthur Alston-Roberts-West''', [[Commander of the Order of the Bath|CVO]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (born 23 November 1937), also known as '''George West''', is a retired [[British Army]] officer and member of the [[Royal Household of the United Kingdom]]. He served as [[Comptroller]] of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]] from 1987 1990.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court and Social: Appointments|newspaper=The Times|date=11 March 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Court Circular|newspaper=The Times|date=12 December 1990}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAlston-Roberts-West was born on 23 November 1937.<ref>{{cite news|title=Birthdays today|newspaper=The Times|date=23 November 1989}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nOn 10 February 1981, he was appointed [[Comptroller|Assistant Comptroller]] of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]].<ref name=\"LG 10 February 1981\">{{London Gazette |issue=48519 |date=10 February 1981 |page=1947 |supp=y }}</ref> On 16 February 1982, he was appointed [[Extra Equerry]] to [[Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=\"LG 16 February 1982\">{{London Gazette |issue=48893 |date=16 February 1982 |page=2153 }}</ref> In December 1987, he was appointed [[Comptroller]] of the Lord Chamberlain's Office in succession to [[John Johnston (courtier)|Sir John Johnston]].<ref name=\"LG 15 December 1987\">{{London Gazette |issue=51153 |date=15 December 1987 |page=15352 }}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Malcolm Ross (courtier)|Malcolm Ross]] on 1 January 1991.<ref name=\"LG 12 February 1991\">{{London Gazette |issue=52447 |date=12 February 1991 |page=2223 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\nIn the 1988 [[New Year Honours]], Alston-Roberts-West was appointed [[Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] (CVO).<ref name=\"LG 30 December 1987\">{{London Gazette |issue=51171 |date=30 December 1987 |page=4 |supp=y }}</ref> In July 2006, he was appointed Serving Brother of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]] (SBStJ).<ref name=\"LG 27 July 2006\">{{London Gazette |issue=58055 |date=27 July 2006 |page=0 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 1988, he was appointed [[Deputy Lieutenant]] (DL) of [[Warwickshire]].<ref name=\"LG 23 November 1988\">{{London Gazette |issue=51538 |date=23 November 1988 |page=13143 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alston-Roberts-West, George}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Grenadier Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the British Royal Household]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Serving Brothers of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n", "text_old": "[[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-Colonel]] '''George Arthur Alston-Roberts-West''', [[Commander of the Order of the Bath|CVO]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (23 November 1937), also known as '''George West''', is a retired [[British Army]] officer and member of the [[Royal Household of the United Kingdom]]. He served as [[Comptroller]] of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]] from 1987 1990.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court and Social: Appointments|newspaper=The Times|date=11 March 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Court Circular|newspaper=The Times|date=12 December 1990}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAlston-Roberts-West was born on 23 November 1937.<ref>{{cite news|title=Birthdays today|newspaper=The Times|date=23 November 1989}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nOn 10 February 1981, he was appointed [[Comptroller|Assistant Comptroller]] of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]].<ref name=\"LG 10 February 1981\">{{London Gazette |issue=48519 |date=10 February 1981 |page=1947 |supp=y }}</ref> On 16 February 1982, he was appointed [[Extra Equerry]] to [[Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=\"LG 16 February 1982\">{{London Gazette |issue=48893 |date=16 February 1982 |page=2153 }}</ref> In December 1987, he was appointed [[Comptroller]] of the Lord Chamberlain's Office in succession to [[John Johnston (courtier)|Sir John Johnston]].<ref name=\"LG 15 December 1987\">{{London Gazette |issue=51153 |date=15 December 1987 |page=15352 }}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Malcolm Ross (courtier)|Malcolm Ross]] on 1 January 1991.<ref name=\"LG 12 February 1991\">{{London Gazette |issue=52447 |date=12 February 1991 |page=2223 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\nIn the 1988 [[New Year Honours]], Alston-Roberts-West was appointed [[Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] (CVO).<ref name=\"LG 30 December 1987\">{{London Gazette |issue=51171 |date=30 December 1987 |page=4 |supp=y }}</ref> In July 2006, he was appointed Serving Brother of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]] (SBStJ).<ref name=\"LG 27 July 2006\">{{London Gazette |issue=58055 |date=27 July 2006 |page=0 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 1988, he was appointed [[Deputy Lieutenant]] (DL) of [[Warwickshire]].<ref name=\"LG 23 November 1988\">{{London Gazette |issue=51538 |date=23 November 1988 |page=13143 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alston-Roberts-West, George}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Grenadier Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the British Royal Household]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Serving Brothers of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n", "name_user": "Necrothesp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Alston-Roberts-West"}
{"title_page": "Women's World Championship", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional wrestling women's championship}}\n{{Infobox pro wrestling championship\n| name = Women's World Championship\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| created =\n| retired =\n| promotion =\n| firstchamp = [[Cora Livingston]]\n| finalchamp = [[June Byers]]\n| mostreigns =\n| longestreign =\n| shortestreign = \n| oldest = <!-- ({{Age in years and days|date 1|date 2}}) -->\n| youngest = <!-- ({{Age in years and days|date 1|date 2}}) -->\n| heaviest = <!-- ({{Convert|POUNDS|lb|kg|abbr=on}}) or ({{Convert|KILOGRAMS|kg|lb}}) -->\n| lightest = <!-- ({{Convert|POUNDS|lb|kg|abbr=on}}) or ({{Convert|KILOGRAMS|kg|lb}}) -->\n| pastnames =\n}}\n\nThe '''Women's World Championship''' was the first [[women's professional wrestling]] world title.<ref name=solomon>{{cite book|isbn=9781617136276|title=Pro Wrestling FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the World's Most Entertaining Spectacle|author=Brian Solomon|year=2015|publisher=Hal Leonard}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Cora Livingston]] defeated  Hazel Parker in 1906. Though the contest was originally for the Featherweight Championship, from that point she was billed as the first women's champion of the world.<ref>https://books.google.com.bd/books?id=f_lsDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Alice%20Williams&f=false</ref> She then went to face women's champion Laura Bennett in a champion vs champion match in 1910. While Livingston was proclaimed as world champion, Laura was simply referred as women's champion. The match saw [[Cora Livingston]] victorious and it was at that time she was officially recognized as the first women's world champion.<ref name=solomon>{{cite book|isbn=9781617136276|title=Pro Wrestling FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the World's Most Entertaining Spectacle|author=Brian Solomon|year=2015|publisher=Hal Leonard}}</ref><ref>https://classicwrestlingarticles.wordpress.com/2014/04/11/mrs-bowser-dies-was-mat-champ/</ref>\n\n[[Mildred Burke]] won a woman's world championship title in 1937 and held it for close to two decades. Mildred Burke won the women's wrestling world championship title defeating Clara Mortenson the inaugural champion.<ref>[https://www.wwe.com/superstars/mildredburke WWE Superstars: Mildred Burke]</ref><ref name=comp>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TQ5pDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=%22women%27s+world+championship%22+wrestling+(mildred%7Cburke)&source=bl&ots=m6Xev6f76C&sig=ACfU3U2eZqEYhzzaIn8N6onu6wtWnQymzg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYkZLZr-DoAhWaK80KHfrxDNY4FBDoATAIegQIDBAx#v=onepage&q=%22women's%20world%20championship%22%20wrestling%20(mildred%7Cburke)&f=false ''Pro Wrestling: a comprehensive reference guide'']</ref> Clara had competed for the vacant championship against Barbara Ware, with Clara coming out victorious, following her victory, she was billed the as the first women's world champion.<ref>http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/c/clara-mortenson/</ref> On June 14, 1953, [[June Byers]] won a 13-woman tournament in [[Baltimore]] to claim the belt. She quickly became a popular [[face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] champion.<ref name=IMDB>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1296643/ June Byers at imdb.com]. Retrieved on 2007-11-11.</ref> Byers and Burke wrestled a [[two out of three falls match]] in 1954 it went to a no contest. Subsequently, Byers was recognized as the [[NWA World Women's Championship|NWA World Women's Champion]], and Burke went on to create the [[WWWA World Championship]] and was recognized as its first champion.<ref name=museum>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwhf.org/halloffamers/bios/burke.asp|title=Mildred Burke|publisher=[[Professional Wrestling Hall of Fame and Museum]]|accessdate=2009-02-20|author=Malnoske, Andrew}}</ref>\n\n==Title history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=16%|Wrestler:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% |Times:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=16%|Date:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=18%|Location:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=45%|Notes:\n|-\n|[[Cora Livingston]]\n|1\n|October 1910\n|[[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City, MO]]\n|Recognized as the first Women's Champion of the World.\n|-\n|colspan=5 style=\"background: #dddddd;\"|''Livingstone retired as champion in 1925.''\n|-\n|[[Clara Mortenson]]\n|1\n|1932\n|\n|Defeated Barbara Ware to win inagural title.{{when|date=April 2020}}{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n|[[Mildred Burke]]\n|1\n|January 28, 1937<ref name=comp/>\n|[[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga, TN]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Clara Mortenson]]<ref name=comp/>\n|2\n|February 11, 1937\n|[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n|Despite having lost the title in 1937, Mortenson was billed as World Champion in her appearance fourteen years later in the 1951 film [[Racket Girls]].\n|-\n|[[Mildred Burke]]<ref name=comp/>\n|2\n|April, 1937\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[June Byers]]\n|1\n|June 14, 1953\n|[[Baltimore|Baltimore, MD]]\n|Byers won a 13-woman tournament to win the vacant championship.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TQ5pDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=%22women%27s+world+championship%22+wrestling+byers&source=bl&ots=m6Xev6f86E&sig=ACfU3U00bCbvTgY6zmfONMEDBA3TAg4kmQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjPp-aJsODoAhVCa80KHZIrALwQ6AEwFnoECBIQLA#v=onepage&q=byers&f=false ''Pro Wrestling: a comprehensive reference guide'']</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=5 style=\"background: #dddddd;\"|''Byers and Burke wrestled a [[two out of three falls match]] in 1954.  The bout went to a no contest. Subsequently, Byers was recognized as the [[NWA World Women's Championship|NWA World Women's Champion]], and Burke went on to create the [[WWWA World Championship]] and was recognized as its first champion. The Women's World Championship was retired in 1954.''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of early world heavyweight champions in professional wrestling]]\n*[[World Heavyweight Wrestling Championship (original version)]]\n*[[Women's World Tag Team Championship (disambiguation)|Women's World Tag Team Championship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:National Wrestling Alliance championships]]\n[[Category:World professional wrestling championships]]\n[[Category:Women's professional wrestling championships]]\n[[Category:1890s establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional wrestling women's championship}}\n{{Infobox pro wrestling championship\n| name = Women's World Championship\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| created =\n| retired =\n| promotion =\n| firstchamp = [[Cora Livingston]]\n| finalchamp = [[June Byers]]\n| mostreigns =\n| longestreign =\n| shortestreign = \n| oldest = <!-- ({{Age in years and days|date 1|date 2}}) -->\n| youngest = <!-- ({{Age in years and days|date 1|date 2}}) -->\n| heaviest = <!-- ({{Convert|POUNDS|lb|kg|abbr=on}}) or ({{Convert|KILOGRAMS|kg|lb}}) -->\n| lightest = <!-- ({{Convert|POUNDS|lb|kg|abbr=on}}) or ({{Convert|KILOGRAMS|kg|lb}}) -->\n| pastnames =\n}}\n\nThe '''Women's World Championship''' was the first [[women's professional wrestling]] world title.<ref name=solomon>{{cite book|isbn=9781617136276|title=Pro Wrestling FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the World's Most Entertaining Spectacle|author=Brian Solomon|year=2015|publisher=Hal Leonard}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Cora Livingston]] defeated  Hazel Parker in 1906. Though the contest was originally for the Featherweight Championship, from that point she was billed as the first women's champion of the world.<ref>https://books.google.com.bd/books?id=f_lsDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Alice%20Williams&f=false</ref> She then went to face women's champion Laura Bennett in a champion vs champion match in 1910. While Livingston was proclaimed as world champion, Laura was simply referred as women's champion. The match saw [[Cora Livingston]] victorious and it was at that time she was officially recognized as the first women's world champion.<ref name=solomon>{{cite book|isbn=9781617136276|title=Pro Wrestling FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the World's Most Entertaining Spectacle|author=Brian Solomon|year=2015|publisher=Hal Leonard}}</ref><ref>https://classicwrestlingarticles.wordpress.com/2014/04/11/mrs-bowser-dies-was-mat-champ/</ref>\n\n[[Mildred Burke]] won a woman's world championship title in 1937 and held it for close to two decades. Mildred Burke won the women's wrestling world championship title defeating Clara Mortenson the inaugural champion.<ref>[https://www.wwe.com/superstars/mildredburke WWE Superstars: Mildred Burke]</ref><ref name=comp>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TQ5pDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=%22women%27s+world+championship%22+wrestling+(mildred%7Cburke)&source=bl&ots=m6Xev6f76C&sig=ACfU3U2eZqEYhzzaIn8N6onu6wtWnQymzg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYkZLZr-DoAhWaK80KHfrxDNY4FBDoATAIegQIDBAx#v=onepage&q=%22women's%20world%20championship%22%20wrestling%20(mildred%7Cburke)&f=false ''Pro Wrestling: a comprehensive reference guide'']</ref> Clara had competed for the the vacant championship against Barbara Ware, with Clara coming out victorious, following her victory, she was billed the as the first women's world champion.<ref>http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/c/clara-mortenson/</ref> On June 14, 1953, [[June Byers]] won a 13-woman tournament in [[Baltimore]] to claim the belt. She quickly became a popular [[face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] champion.<ref name=IMDB>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1296643/ June Byers at imdb.com]. Retrieved on 2007-11-11.</ref> Byers and Burke wrestled a [[two out of three falls match]] in 1954 it went to a no contest. Subsequently, Byers was recognized as the [[NWA World Women's Championship|NWA World Women's Champion]], and Burke went on to create the [[WWWA World Championship]] and was recognized as its first champion.<ref name=museum>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwhf.org/halloffamers/bios/burke.asp|title=Mildred Burke|publisher=[[Professional Wrestling Hall of Fame and Museum]]|accessdate=2009-02-20|author=Malnoske, Andrew}}</ref>\n\n==Title history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=16%|Wrestler:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% |Times:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=16%|Date:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=18%|Location:\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=45%|Notes:\n|-\n|[[Cora Livingston]]\n|1\n|October 1910\n|[[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City, MO]]\n|Recognized as the first Women's Champion of the World.\n|-\n|colspan=5 style=\"background: #dddddd;\"|''Livingstone retired as champion in 1925.''\n|-\n|[[Clara Mortenson]]\n|1\n|1932\n|\n|Defeated Barbara Ware to win inagural title.{{when|date=April 2020}}{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n|[[Mildred Burke]]\n|1\n|January 28, 1937<ref name=comp/>\n|[[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga, TN]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Clara Mortenson]]<ref name=comp/>\n|2\n|February 11, 1937\n|[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n|Despite having lost the title in 1937, Mortenson was billed as World Champion in her appearance fourteen years later in the 1951 film [[Racket Girls]].\n|-\n|[[Mildred Burke]]<ref name=comp/>\n|2\n|April, 1937\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[June Byers]]\n|1\n|June 14, 1953\n|[[Baltimore|Baltimore, MD]]\n|Byers won a 13-woman tournament to win the vacant championship.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TQ5pDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=%22women%27s+world+championship%22+wrestling+byers&source=bl&ots=m6Xev6f86E&sig=ACfU3U00bCbvTgY6zmfONMEDBA3TAg4kmQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjPp-aJsODoAhVCa80KHZIrALwQ6AEwFnoECBIQLA#v=onepage&q=byers&f=false ''Pro Wrestling: a comprehensive reference guide'']</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=5 style=\"background: #dddddd;\"|''Byers and Burke wrestled a [[two out of three falls match]] in 1954.  The bout went to a no contest. Subsequently, Byers was recognized as the [[NWA World Women's Championship|NWA World Women's Champion]], and Burke went on to create the [[WWWA World Championship]] and was recognized as its first champion. The Women's World Championship was retired in 1954.''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of early world heavyweight champions in professional wrestling]]\n*[[World Heavyweight Wrestling Championship (original version)]]\n*[[Women's World Tag Team Championship (disambiguation)|Women's World Tag Team Championship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:National Wrestling Alliance championships]]\n[[Category:World professional wrestling championships]]\n[[Category:Women's professional wrestling championships]]\n[[Category:1890s establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_World_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Krassimira Daskalova", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Krassimira Daskalova\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0414\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1957}}<!--  For people who have died, use {{Birth date|1957|06|04|df=y}} -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1957|06|04|df=y}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Bulgarian\n| other_names   = Krasimira Daskalova, Krassimira Petrova Daskalova\n| occupation    = academic\n| years_active  = 1992\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Krassimira Daskalova''' ({{lang-bg|\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0414\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430}}, born 1957) is a Bulgarian academic and pioneer in [[gender studies]]. She served as editor of ''L'Homme: European Journal of Feminist History'' from 2003 to 2011 and is co-editor of ''[[Aspasia (journal)|Aspasia]]'' since 2007. Between 2005 and 2010 she was president of the [[International Federation for Research in Women's History]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nKrassimira Daskalova was born in 1957<!-- 4 June 1957 -->{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|p=1}} and grew up in Ruse, Bulgaria. She graduated from the Hristo Botev Gymnasium in Ruse in 1975 and entered [[Sofia University]] the following year.{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|p=3}} After completing her master's degree in 1981,{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=1}} she worked in the State Historical Archive in Ruse as a research assistant until 1982.{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|p=2}} In 1983, she began working conducting historical and sociological research at the Center for Cultural Studies at Sofia University. The aim of her research  was to assist in compiling the ''\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0432\u044a\u0437\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044f'' (''Bulgarian Revival Intelligentsia'') an encyclopedia published in 1988.{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=1}} The following year, Daskalova began her PhD studies{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|p=2}} and successfully defended her thesis in 1992.{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=1}}  A [[polyglot]], Daskalova speaks and has published in Bulgarian, English, French, German, Italian, Russian and Serbian.{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|pp=3\u20134}}{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=2}} She has completed post-graduate research on scholarships and fellowships from the [[Fulbright Program]], the [[German Academic Exchange Service]], the [[Institute for Human Sciences]], the Japanese Association of University Women, and the [[K\u00f6rber Foundation]], among others.{{sfn|Radcliffe Institute|2013}}\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1992 to 2000, Daskalova taught as an assistant professor in library sciences and history, before being promoted to associate professor in 2000.{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|p=1}}{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=2}} Her two main focuses in teaching and research are the history of literature and the history women and\ngender relations.{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=2}} She has written about the origins of the Bulgarian women's movement in the 1850s, during the [[Ottoman Empire]], as well as barriers to women's education and access to professions, which persisted in law and medicine until 1945.{{sfn|\u0414\u0430\u043c\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430|2008}} One of the pioneers in Bulgarian [[gender studies]], she assisted in founding the academic discipline from the early 1990s. Introducing interdisciplinary comparative studies, Daskalova has evaluated discussion on methodological issues in documenting historic gendered studies, analyzed women's identity in the culture over time, and studied the representation of women in traditional textbooks.{{sfn|\u041a\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=1}} Her work has often uncovered narratives with meticulous research which were in conflict with the \"official perspective of historical events\".{{sfn|\u041a\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=3}}\n\nFrom 2003 to 2011, Daskalova served as editor at the academic journal ''L'Homme: European Journal of Feminist History'' and from 2007, she had been co-editor of ''[[Aspasia (journal)|Aspasia]]''.{{sfn|Radcliffe Institute|2013}}{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=10}} Her 2004 book, ''Voices of Their Own: Oral History Interviews of Women'' brought together a broad spectrum of women, from different ethnic backgrounds, who held diverse religious and political beliefs, and represented different levels of educational training and social class. The interviews were centered on the family and sought to gather information on the changing state of women in the twentieth century.{{sfn|Popa|2007|pp=278\u2013279}} Her 2006 book, ''A Biographical Dictionary of Women's Movements and Feminisms: Central, Eastern, and South Eastern Europe, 19th and 20th Centuries'' which was co-edited by [[Francisca de Haan]] and Anna Loutfi was honored that year by [[Choice Reviews]] with an \"Outstanding Academic Title\" award.{{sfn|Radcliffe Institute|2013}}{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=9}} \n\nBetween 2004 and 2008, Daskalova was chair on the board of the Bulgarian Association of University Women.{{sfn|\u041f\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0430|2019}} From 2005 to 2010, she served as president of the [[International Federation for Research in Women's History]].{{sfn|Radcliffe Institute|2013}}{{sfn|International Federation for Research in Women's History|2007}} In 2009, she was involved in the launching of Sofia University's masters degree program in Women's and Gender History.{{sfn|\u0414\u0430\u043c\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430|2008}} In 2012, Daskalova was promoted full professor,{{sfn|Daskalova|2016|p=1}} after extensive review by her peers.{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=1}}{{sfn|\u041a\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=1}} Her book, ''\u0416\u0435\u043d\u0438, \u043f\u043e\u043b \u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f, 1878\u20131944'' (Women, Gender and Modernization in Bulgaria, 1878\u20131944), published in 2012, treated the topic of sexuality and prostitution, which had not previously been evaluated in Bulgaria's history.{{sfn|\u0413\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0430|2012|p=10}} Daskalova manages the first European master's degree program in women's and gender history. The program is operated as a consortium of scholars from participating universities of [[Central European University]] (Hungary), [[Lumi\u00e8re University Lyon 2]] (France), [[Ruhr University Bochum]] (Germany), Sofia University (Bulgaria), the [[University of Padua]] (Italy), and the [[University of Vienna]] (Austria). Completing the program requires that students take at least one semester of courses at each partner.{{sfn|\u041f\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0430|2019}}\n\n==Selected works==\n*{{cite book |last1=Daskalova |first1=Krassimira |title=Literacy and Reading in 19th Century Bulgaria |series=The Donald W. Treadgold Papers in Russian, East European and Central Asian Studies |volume=12 |date=1997 |publisher=Henry M. Jackson School of International Studies |location=Seattle, Washington |oclc=68466801}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Daskalova |first1=Krassimira |editor-last1=Scott |editor-first1=Joan Wallach |editor-last2=Kaplan |editor-first2=Cora |editor-last3=Keates |editor-first3=Debra |title=Transitions, Environments, Translations: Feminisms in International Politics |date=1997 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=London |chapter=14. The Women's Movement in Bulgaria After Communism |isbn=978-0-415-91541-0 |pages=162-175}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Daskalova |first1=Krassimira |title=Establishing a Women's History Course on Women in Bulgarian Society, 1840-1940, at Sofia University |journal=[[Women's History Review]] |volume=9 |issue=1 |date=March 2000 |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |location=London |doi=10.1080/09612020000200229 |issn=0961-2025 |oclc=4649343568 |pages=149-153}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Daskalova |editor1-first=Krassimira |editor2-last=Muharska and |editor2-first=Ralitsa (translator) |editor3-last=Stoitsova |editor3-first=Elitsa (translator) |title=Voices of their Own: Oral History Interviews of Women |date=2004 |publisher=Polis Publishers |location=Sofia, Bulgaria |isbn=978-954-796-008-4}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=de Haan |editor1-first=Francisca |editor2-last=Daskalova |editor2-first=Krasimira |editor3-last=Loutfi |editor3-first=Anna |title=Biographical Dictionary of Women's Movements and Feminisms in Central, Eastern, and South Eastern Europe: 19th and 20th Centuries |date=2006 |publisher=Central European University Press |location=Budapest, Hungary |isbn=978-963-7326-39-4 |edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last1=Hellsten |editor-first1=Sirkku K. |editor-last2=Holli |editor-first2=Anne Maria |editor-last3=Daskalova |editor-first3=Krassimira |title=Women's Citizenship and Political Rights |year=2006 |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] |location=Basingstoke, Hampshire |isbn=978-0-230-50290-1}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last1=Daskalova |editor-first1=Krassimira |editor-last2=Tomi\u0107 |editor-first2=Caroline Hornstein |editor-last3=Kaser |editor-first3=Karl |editor-last4=Radunovi\u0107 |editor-first4=Filip |title=Gendering Post-socialist Transition: Studies of Changing Gender Perspectives |series=ERSTE Stiftung |volume=1|date=2012 |publisher=LIT Verlag |location=M\u00fcnster |isbn=978-3-643-90229-0}}\n*{{cite book |last1=\u0414\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430 |first1=\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 |title=\u0416\u0435\u043d\u0438, \u043f\u043e\u043b \u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f, 1878-1944 |date=2012 |publisher=\u0423\u0418 \"\u0421\u0432. \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u041e\u0445\u0440\u0438\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\" |location=Sofia, Bulgaria |isbn=978-954-07-3319-7 |language=Bulgarian |trans-title=Women, Gender and Modernization in Bulgaria, 1878-1944}}\n*{{cite book |last=Daskalova |first=Krasimira |editor-last1=Rodr\u00edguez-Ruiz |editor-first1=Blanca |editor-last2=Rubio-Mar\u00edn |editor-first2=Ruth |title=The Struggle for Female Suffrage in Europe: Voting to Become Citizens |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3KIMwdbG0EcC&pg=PA321 |year=2012 |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |location=Leiden, The Netherlands |isbn=978-90-04-22425-4 |chapter=Women's Suffrage in Bulgaria |pages=321-338}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite news |ref=harv |last1=\u0414\u0430\u043c\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 |first1=\u042e\u043b\u0438\u044f |title=\u0424\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043c\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430 \u043e\u0449\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437 19-\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043a |url=http://www.dw.com/bg/\u0444\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043c\u044a\u0442-\u0432-\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u0441\u0435-\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430-